A dog was left trapped in a vehicle on a day the UK is expected to experience some of the hottest temperatures ever recorded across the nation. Metropolitan Police smashed through the window to get the animal out at The Royal Air Force Museum in Hendon – as the area hit 31.5°C. Officers from the North West Basic Command Unit slammed the situation as ‘unbelievable’ on social media. Writing in capital letters to express their anger, they put: ‘JUST DON’T TAKE DOGS OUT IN THIS HEAT.’ It is not yet known if the dog was harmed in the incident. Metro.co.uk has contacted the Barnet MPS/North West BCU for more information. Just hours before the same police department had issued a warning, saying: ‘Never leave your dog alone in a car on a warm day. #DogsDieInHotCars’. Writing on Twitter, they had posted a link to a page on the RSPCA website offering advice on what to do if you see a dog in a car on a warm day. It also came hours after a retired police officer posted a picture of an infrared thermometer showing temperatures of 59.5°C in his car. He wrote: ‘Interior of my car at 11am. Not even the hottest part of the day yet. ‘Hope none of my old colleagues need to break into a car today due to an irresponsible dog owner.’ He later reposted the Barnet MPS’s tweet, saying: ‘Spoke too soon…’ Get in touch with our news team by emailing us at webnews@metro.co.uk. For more stories like this, check our news page.